Round 1
[Patient] What foods should I eat to help my heart failure?
[Educator] Focus on fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins like fish or chicken.

Round 2
[Patient] Are there any specific fruits that are good for heart failure?
[Educator] Berries like strawberries, blueberries, and raspberries are great choices for your heart.

Round 3
[Patient] Can I still eat fried foods?
[Educator] It's best to limit fried foods as they can be high in unhealthy fats.

Round 4
[Patient] What about salt?
[Educator] Try to reduce your salt intake; it can make your heart failure worse.

Round 5
[Patient] Are there any drinks I should avoid?
[Educator] Limit sugary drinks like soda and energy drinks, they can be harmful for your heart.

Round 6
[Patient] Can I have coffee?
[Educator] Coffee in moderation is okay, but too much caffeine can be harmful for your heart.

Round 7
[Patient] What about alcohol?
[Educator] It's best to limit alcohol intake as it can weaken your heart.

Round 8
[Patient] Should I be eating dairy products?
[Educator] Choose low-fat or fat-free dairy products to help your heart stay healthy.

Round 9
[Patient] Are there any specific vegetables I should focus on?
[Educator] Dark leafy greens like spinach and kale are great choices for your heart health.

Round 10
[Patient] Can I have desserts?
[Educator] Opt for healthier dessert options like fruit or yogurt instead of sugary treats.

Round 11
[Patient] What about fast food?
[Educator] Try to avoid fast food as it is often high in unhealthy fats and salt.

Round 12
[Patient] Should I be eating red meat?
[Educator] Limit your intake of red meat and opt for lean protein sources like poultry or fish.

Round 13
[Patient] Can I eat nuts?
[Educator] Nuts are a good source of healthy fats, but enjoy them in moderation.

Round 14
[Patient] What about processed foods?
[Educator] Try to limit processed foods as they can be high in unhealthy additives and preservatives.

Round 15
[Patient] Thank you for the food recommendations, I will try to make healthier choices.
[Educator] You're welcome! Making small changes can have a big impact on your heart health.